<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1865-02-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1865-02-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="84" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d84">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1265.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                        of State</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1865-02-21"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 21, 1865</date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>. Your despatch of the 26th of January, No.
                            865, has been received. I thank you for the very careful survey it
                            presents of British national sentiment <pb facs="0204" n="164" xml:id="pg_164"/> in regard to our civil war, and for your judicious
                            suggestions touching the con-duct of our affairs in the present crisis.
                            Judging from recent indications, the desire for separation in the south
                            is not now intense enough to induce a resort to the measure of universal
                            emancipation.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams</hi>. Esq.,<hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>